1
00:00:00,672 --> 00:00:02,053
Foundation Course 2.

2
00:00:02,573 --> 00:00:03,234
Talk to.

3
00:00:04,315 --> 00:00:06,057
Guilt, real and unreal.

4
00:00:07,599 --> 00:00:12,326
Guilt and feelings associated with guilt are sometimes a great problem for meditators.

5
00:00:13,026 --> 00:00:14,247
They can be very insistent.

6
00:00:15,208 --> 00:00:21,437
Some say it's to do with their Christian upbringing, or guilt only arises because of the concept of a vengeful deity.

7
00:00:22,757 --> 00:00:30,207
But guilt is a human phenomena, and each individual suffers their own particular amount of it, depending on their understanding and the offense committed.

8
00:00:31,655 --> 00:00:43,590
If the search for pleasure and the self-identification with pleasurable things brings about a syndrome of emotional responses, guilt also creates such a one, but a wholly different set of reactions.

9
00:00:44,811 --> 00:00:49,177
Guilt itself is just the knowledge of having done something against one's conscience.

10
00:00:50,158 --> 00:00:54,304
Conscience here means simply knowing, but a knowing of a particular kind.

11
00:00:55,145 --> 00:00:57,948
It is the knowing of what is right and what is wrong.

12
00:00:59,127 --> 00:01:05,593
In Buddhism, it is better to talk of what is right and wrong in terms of skillfulness or unwholesomeness.

13
00:01:08,016 --> 00:01:10,819
Everyone has a conscience, and every conscience is different.

14
00:01:11,579 --> 00:01:20,188
Even though there is a broad agreement about such things as murder and theft, when it comes to the outer reaches of our definitions, the edges get frayed.

15
00:01:21,670 --> 00:01:24,472
Is it right to execute someone who has killed another?

16
00:01:25,674 --> 00:01:28,897
At what point is abortion the killing of a human being?

17
00:01:30,194 --> 00:01:34,939
Our conscience tells us what is wholesome for us, or what is unwholesome for us.

18
00:01:36,542 --> 00:01:43,451
This conscience, then, is our moral wisdom, and therefore contains within it right or wrong understanding.

19
00:01:44,453 --> 00:01:55,628
This understanding determines our intentions and acts of will, which in turn determine our karma, so it is obviously very important to investigate conscience closely.

20
00:01:56,873 --> 00:02:01,599
We need to question all our understandings and opinions about morality, good and bad.

21
00:02:02,641 --> 00:02:05,945
The Buddha makes it quite clear that ignorance is no excuse.

22
00:02:06,887 --> 00:02:11,212
Being ignorant will not save us from the consequences of an unwholesome act.

23
00:02:12,895 --> 00:02:14,798
This is a verse from the Dhammapada.

24
00:02:15,705 --> 00:02:21,074
A fool, while he performs unskillful deeds, does not know them to be unskillful.

25
00:02:21,955 --> 00:02:26,923
But that fool still suffers for his unskillfulness, just as one burnt by fire.

26
00:02:29,086 --> 00:02:38,079
In other words, a child, just because she doesn't know what matches do and still plays with them even after parental warnings, will still be burnt.

27
00:02:38,439 --> 00:02:39,942
She may even burn the house down.

28
00:02:40,816 --> 00:02:46,144
We are not isolated individuals, we are an integral part of an interrelated world.

29
00:02:46,944 --> 00:02:49,487
If we do harm, harm comes back to us.

30
00:02:50,469 --> 00:03:00,743
So knowing what is unwholesome and unskillful is of great importance to us if we want to put an end to the suffering we cause ourselves and unjustly to other human beings.

31
00:03:04,049 --> 00:03:10,418
So having a conscience means that whenever we do something we know it to be wholesome, unwholesome or neutral.

32
00:03:11,325 --> 00:03:14,128
When we know that, what we have done is wholesome.

33
00:03:14,849 --> 00:03:15,912
Pleasant feelings arise.

34
00:03:16,712 --> 00:03:18,054
Our self-esteem grows.

35
00:03:19,195 --> 00:03:23,099
The proverbial helping of the old person across the road makes one feel good.

36
00:03:23,841 --> 00:03:26,604
To do good is to feel good about oneself.

37
00:03:27,586 --> 00:03:31,730
It dispels feeling of self-hate, self-belittlement.

38
00:03:31,751 --> 00:03:40,741
On the other hand, if while driving my car, an old person steps onto the zebra crossing and screeching to a halt, I wind down my window and shout, "'Abuse!'

39
00:03:41,110 --> 00:03:49,781
to the effect that all people ought to be done away with as kindly as possible, afterwards, if I am truthful with myself, I shall know myself to have been cruel.

40
00:03:51,323 --> 00:03:54,747
I have gone against my knowledge of what is wholesome and skilful.

41
00:03:55,207 --> 00:03:56,590
I have crossed my conscience.

42
00:03:57,812 --> 00:04:00,694
This knowing that I have transgressed a moral law is guilt.

43
00:04:01,376 --> 00:04:10,627
The dictionary definition talks of failure to do one's duty, the fact of having committed an offence, the state of having willfully committed a crime.

44
00:04:14,168 --> 00:04:15,650
Now we can see what guilt is.

45
00:04:16,430 --> 00:04:19,975
It is simply knowing one has done what one ought not to do.

46
00:04:21,216 --> 00:04:25,502
It is perfectly right and proper in such a case to feel and know oneself to be guilty.

47
00:04:26,764 --> 00:04:31,490
Knowing oneself to be guilty is just awareness of having done something harmful.

48
00:04:32,932 --> 00:04:38,860
Now this knowledge is accompanied by two feelings in Buddhist psychology, shame and dread.

49
00:04:39,802 --> 00:04:47,509
Shame is just those varying degrees of embarrassment, plus the knowledge that one has lost the respect of others and self-respect.

50
00:04:48,971 --> 00:04:52,915
If I'm caught shoplifting a battery for my Walkman, I feel so small.

51
00:04:53,615 --> 00:04:54,536
I feel humiliated.

52
00:04:55,478 --> 00:05:00,744
I know people now see me not as a worthy citizen, but as a petty thief.

53
00:05:00,764 --> 00:05:02,646
Shame can be a very painful experience.

54
00:05:03,326 --> 00:05:06,670
Knowing this sets a barrier, a protection against me doing such things.

55
00:05:07,762 --> 00:05:11,666
You used to hear parents say to young people, Have you no shame?

56
00:05:11,887 --> 00:05:12,767
Don't you feel ashamed?

57
00:05:13,528 --> 00:05:19,375
It's gone out of fashion now because of our general rejection of guilt as a good thing, and the fear of creating a guilt complex.

58
00:05:20,755 --> 00:05:30,846
But in Buddhist understanding, guilt has a proper role to play, and it is entwined with self-esteem and self-respect, and the esteem and respect others have of us.

59
00:05:32,968 --> 00:05:34,850
Perhaps we ought to say to our children,

60
00:05:35,067 --> 00:05:36,389
Have you no self-respect?

61
00:05:36,869 --> 00:05:38,151
Don't you want to be respected?

62
00:05:38,851 --> 00:05:41,235
It may be a more positive way of saying the same thing.

63
00:05:43,398 --> 00:05:46,661
Now, at the same time as feeling ashamed, I also feel afraid.

64
00:05:47,483 --> 00:05:50,105
For when I'm caught red-handed, dread also arises.

65
00:05:50,125 --> 00:05:52,509
I fear the consequences of my act.

66
00:05:53,110 --> 00:05:55,033
I know I can be prosecuted or fined.

67
00:05:55,293 --> 00:05:56,413
I may even lose my job.

68
00:05:57,516 --> 00:06:02,442
Knowing there are inescapable consequences for what I do also creates a barrier.

69
00:06:02,641 --> 00:06:06,084
a protection against my doing unskillful, unwholesome acts.

70
00:06:07,526 --> 00:06:21,339
The Buddha, again in the Dhammapada, warns us, not in the sky, nor in the middle of the ocean, nor in a cave of a mountain, nor anywhere else is there a place where we can escape from the consequences of an unwholesome deed.

71
00:06:24,122 --> 00:06:25,824
There's a story concerning this verse.

72
00:06:26,725 --> 00:06:30,689
It was the answer the Buddha gave to some monks who told him about this strange event.

73
00:06:31,345 --> 00:06:35,891
they had been travelling on a boat which suddenly stopped mid-water and apparently refused to move.

74
00:06:36,752 --> 00:06:40,956
The people on the boat drew lots, and three times it fell to the wife of the skipper.

75
00:06:42,197 --> 00:06:50,028
He decided he didn't want so many people to suffer on account of his wife, so he had a sandbag tied round her neck and had her thrown overboard.

76
00:06:51,389 --> 00:06:57,437
Now, to our modern ears, this might seem highly suspicious, and a clever way of ridding himself of a troublesome wife.

77
00:06:58,074 --> 00:07:05,041
But the commentary goes on to say that this was the consequence of having drowned a pet dog, because she had been made to feel ashamed of it.

78
00:07:05,862 --> 00:07:11,829
A heavy consequence indeed, though it's nice to see animals being given the high regard they deserve as fellow beings.

79
00:07:13,870 --> 00:07:25,163
In Buddhist understanding, these two reactions to doing harm, shame and dread, are not only the guardians that prevent someone from committing an unskillful act, but also the guardians of order in a society.

80
00:07:26,036 --> 00:07:31,004
If people felt neither shame nor dread of consequences, what would stop them from doing harm?

81
00:07:31,745 --> 00:07:35,951
In fact, such people are often described as psychopathic, mentally ill.

82
00:07:37,194 --> 00:07:49,834
The fact about hardened criminals is that personal gain seems to get the better of discretion, of shame and dread, even though their actions may make others suffer a great deal and bring great suffering to themselves.

83
00:07:51,163 --> 00:07:57,630
In the case of violent political actions, all such considerations are discarded in favour of the ideology.

84
00:07:58,190 --> 00:07:59,653
The ends justify the means.

85
00:08:00,273 --> 00:08:02,336
It's right and proper to kill opponents.

86
00:08:05,298 --> 00:08:20,074
Now, if there is such a thing as a balanced conscience whose guardians are shame and dread, and if there is such a thing as a moral code of behaviour that is the foundation of social and interpersonal harmony, why has guilt become such a great problem for us?

87
00:08:21,016 --> 00:08:22,819
Let's take a typical case.

88
00:08:23,781 --> 00:08:28,088
Billy, a lively lad, found an easy supply of comics and sweets.

89
00:08:29,089 --> 00:08:31,593
He just makes sure no one's looking while he helps himself.

90
00:08:33,015 --> 00:08:37,724
When Billy's finally caught, his parents are very upset and the first thing they tell him is that he's a thief.

91
00:08:38,384 --> 00:08:40,008
Being a thief is bad, very bad.

92
00:08:40,889 --> 00:08:44,154
Therefore, Billy comes to understand that he's a thief and he's bad.

93
00:08:44,894 --> 00:08:48,999
Billy has been told he's bad, off and on, every time he upsets his parents.

94
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:55,206
He's alternatively selfish, cruel, lazy, good for nothing, a nuisance, a why we put up with you will never know.

95
00:08:57,028 --> 00:09:00,873
A part of Billy knows himself to be Bad Billy, Big Bad Billy.

96
00:09:02,313 --> 00:09:08,741
It becomes a self-definition, and with it, low self-esteem, low self-respect, that is, self-hate.

97
00:09:10,783 --> 00:09:14,749
Identifying the action with the actor creates a wrong identity.

98
00:09:15,302 --> 00:09:21,452
No doubt, the act of stealing is not something to encourage in children, but one theft doesn't make a thief.

99
00:09:21,812 --> 00:09:28,663
In fact, a million thefts don't make a thief, if by thief we mean someone who is a thief by nature.

100
00:09:30,726 --> 00:09:36,836
Once we're taught as children to get into these traps of self-definitions, it's very difficult to find an escape.

101
00:09:38,318 --> 00:09:43,167
This sort of guilt is not the proper guilt about an action committed,

102
00:09:43,635 --> 00:09:47,740
but a neurotic guilt about the person who committed the action.

103
00:09:49,280 --> 00:09:57,028
So my fear of consequences is compounded by the fear that that's the sort of person I am and I can't do anything about it.

104
00:09:58,489 --> 00:10:11,600
The understanding that humans are somehow essentially evil, some more than others, bad at the core, so to speak, is a chief cause of mistaken self-definition and later leads to all our problems with guilt.

105
00:10:13,302 --> 00:10:23,095
The Buddha taught that we were born in ignorance, that because of our ignorance we acted with wrong intention, but always with the idea of fulfilling our desires.

106
00:10:24,316 --> 00:10:31,346
Not knowing what desires led to suffering for ourselves and others, and what desires lead to happiness, is the essential problem.

107
00:10:32,486 --> 00:10:39,917
At fundament, the human is wise, is enlightened, is a Buddha, meaning someone who has the potential to be enlightened.

108
00:10:41,197 --> 00:11:10,090
if we truly grasp this point that it is our ignorance that must be dispelled that we are not essentially evil then in our meditation we must allow these damning self-definitions to emerge these voices must be listened to you're useless you're inadequate you're wicked and evil you're terrible no one can love you you can't love anyone and so on through the power of our intuitive wisdom we see these as disembodied voices

109
00:11:10,373 --> 00:11:12,716
voices we have taken into ourselves.

110
00:11:13,818 --> 00:11:20,570
The personality is but a collection of such habits, and just as habits are formed, so they can be unformed.

111
00:11:21,991 --> 00:11:36,836
Meditation should help us to confront these often painful self-definitions, see them as mere opinions, as changeable, and by not indulging them, through this understanding allow their power over our thinking to die out.

112
00:11:39,989 --> 00:11:46,899
Meanwhile, poor Billy, although he was caught, didn't take the opportunity to clear his heart of all the offences.

113
00:11:47,921 --> 00:11:52,908
He swore in tears that he had only ever taken one comic and one bag of sweets.

114
00:11:53,808 --> 00:11:59,998
That's why he was let off lightly with warnings of lashings and thrashings, if ever he should even think of doing such a thing again.

115
00:12:01,520 --> 00:12:08,510
Unfortunately for Billy, guilt feelings, especially of the fear of being found out, sit uncomfortably in his mind.

116
00:12:09,351 --> 00:12:15,780
Since no one does find out, Billy represses those feelings and begins to see this as a clever ploy.

117
00:12:17,182 --> 00:12:23,652
He's now compounded his stealing with lying, and both have been fairly successful in satisfying his desires.

118
00:12:24,552 --> 00:12:28,698
But the result of this is to laden his mind with all sorts of unresolved guilts.

119
00:12:30,041 --> 00:12:34,746
Since boyhood, Billy hasn't stolen a thing, but feelings of guilt still dog him.

120
00:12:35,548 --> 00:12:37,991
Whenever a policeman should appear, panic arises.

121
00:12:38,461 --> 00:12:53,701
Worse, whenever he does do anything wrong, the proper guilt he ought to feel is fuelled by all the unresolved guilt, so that he feels overly guilty and anxious, and has to apologise profusely even when he inadvertently steps on someone's toe.

122
00:12:56,517 --> 00:13:11,754
It is also possible that such is the store of unresolved guilt, coupled with self-definition of being a bad person, that his worldview is so distorted he sees all sorts of people out to get him, conspiracy everywhere, paranoia at worst.

123
00:13:13,075 --> 00:13:16,899
Again, it is in meditation that these phantom guilts can be dealt with.

124
00:13:17,760 --> 00:13:19,162
Let them come to the attention.

125
00:13:19,702 --> 00:13:20,524
Feel them fully.

126
00:13:20,984 --> 00:13:21,904
Accept them fully.

127
00:13:22,605 --> 00:13:26,169
Don't criticize or look for excuses and scapegoats.

128
00:13:26,504 --> 00:13:28,186
Don't get into conversation with them.

129
00:13:28,625 --> 00:13:29,226
Let them be.

130
00:13:29,927 --> 00:13:34,511
Just let them disclose themselves and sit equanimously within all the discomfort.

131
00:13:35,192 --> 00:13:37,195
Slowly, their strength declines.

132
00:13:37,715 --> 00:13:38,875
Their power dissolves.

133
00:13:44,020 --> 00:13:48,225
Unfortunately, yet again, Billy is to be pitied.

134
00:13:48,885 --> 00:13:55,852
The more, for his parents have told him that even bad thoughts are something he should be ashamed of and feel guilty about.

135
00:13:56,827 --> 00:13:58,529
The Buddha's teaching is very clear on this.

136
00:13:59,129 --> 00:14:03,975
Thoughts and images that arise in the mind are the consequences, the results of past actions.

137
00:14:05,296 --> 00:14:10,760
When Billy walks into a newsagent, the idea arises of stealing a book, to slip one inside his coat.

138
00:14:11,841 --> 00:14:14,764
That idea has been conditioned by Billy's past actions.

139
00:14:15,745 --> 00:14:18,288
It has become a conditioned response whenever he sees books.

140
00:14:19,448 --> 00:14:25,114
Up to this point, what Billy is suffering from is the karmic results of past actions, the viparka.

141
00:14:26,274 --> 00:14:28,638
He has not yet committed any new karma.

142
00:14:29,700 --> 00:14:31,201
What happens next is crucial.

143
00:14:32,062 --> 00:14:36,549
If Billy is taken to the idea, it will obsess, possess his mind.

144
00:14:37,611 --> 00:14:39,413
He will make a decision to take the book.

145
00:14:40,395 --> 00:14:45,302
Billy, by this decision, has only reinforced the thought, the intention of stealing.

146
00:14:46,585 --> 00:14:48,147
On the other hand, he may exert himself.

147
00:14:48,527 --> 00:14:51,692
He may even put the book in his coat and then decide against it.

148
00:14:52,499 --> 00:15:03,751
If he takes his action up to this point, he has reinforced his inclination to steal, but we cannot yet say he has stolen, or that he has created any new karma in the sense of a completed unwholesome action.

149
00:15:04,714 --> 00:15:09,538
It is only when these three components all come together can we talk of a karmic action.

150
00:15:10,240 --> 00:15:16,147
The intention, the effort or exertion, and the actual completion of the act.

151
00:15:16,967 --> 00:15:20,312
In this case, when Billy walks out of the shop with the book.

152
00:15:21,793 --> 00:15:33,166
Up until this actual moment of taking, Billy is only reinforcing his state of mind, the mental habit, which will have the unwholesome result of making further temptations harder to overcome.

153
00:15:35,589 --> 00:15:38,591
These are the consequences of intention and exertion.

154
00:15:39,413 --> 00:15:47,480
But upon the actual completion of the act, the stealing itself, not only is there the inner consequence, but the outer consequence too.

155
00:15:48,034 --> 00:15:56,005
At some point in time, because we are all interrelated, interfused, a result will arise from that harmful, unskillful action.

156
00:15:58,109 --> 00:16:06,701
In the Dhammapada, the Buddha warns us, even an unskillful person may still find happiness, so long as his unskillfulness does not bear fruit.

157
00:16:07,381 --> 00:16:12,048
But when his unskillfulness does bear fruit, he will meet with unwholesome consequences.

158
00:16:13,730 --> 00:16:14,851
Let us recap a moment.

159
00:16:15,322 --> 00:16:21,509
Firstly, we can say that unwholesome actions have the same root cause as sensual pleasure.

160
00:16:22,250 --> 00:16:25,174
We do them because we think they will bring us pleasure and happiness.

161
00:16:26,157 --> 00:16:30,763
A biting remark fulfills our desire for revenge, and our self-esteem is restored.

162
00:16:31,683 --> 00:16:35,769
Robbing a bank will bring us all that lovely lolly, and we'll be happy for the rest of our lives.

163
00:16:37,191 --> 00:16:42,038
Sometimes we do things harmful for the sheer sake of excitement, such as driving in a dangerous way.

164
00:16:42,996 --> 00:16:50,509
Whatever the pleasurable satisfaction we gain, it is gained at the expense of ourselves and quite unjustly at the expense of others.

165
00:16:53,813 --> 00:16:57,600
Secondly, we can see that there are two rounds involved.

166
00:16:57,620 --> 00:17:03,288
The first is unskillful actions with guilt feelings that bring success and leads to repetition.

167
00:17:04,130 --> 00:17:10,539
The second is unskillful action that arouses no guilt feelings but lead to painful consequences later.

168
00:17:11,853 --> 00:17:22,209
Thirdly, we cannot say that an unwholesome karmic action is fully completed till the three ingredients are there, intention, exertion and completion of the act.

169
00:17:23,891 --> 00:17:32,144
Fourthly, these guilt rounds with their attendant feelings of shame and dread subsist the pleasure syndrome and go to make life harder for us.

170
00:17:33,266 --> 00:17:35,288
Making money to get rich is one thing.

171
00:17:36,089 --> 00:17:39,295
Making money out of the sale of arms to get rich is another.

172
00:17:40,304 --> 00:17:48,455
Worse still, when all this is fueled by unresolved guilt, it all adds up to create greater anxiety, worry, fear, and restlessness.

173
00:17:50,057 --> 00:17:52,240
In meditation, this now becomes a great hindrance.

174
00:17:53,282 --> 00:17:58,069
When restlessness and anxiety arise in the mind, we need to see if they are coming from guilt.

175
00:17:59,372 --> 00:18:04,219
To our surprise, we may find memories there of unwholesome actions we've done, even as children.

176
00:18:05,498 --> 00:18:10,464
In my own case, when I was about 12 years old, I caught a mole and took it to my teacher.

177
00:18:11,247 --> 00:18:12,127
It was a great catch.

178
00:18:12,788 --> 00:18:16,074
It caused a sensation, and I was for a while a celebrity.

179
00:18:17,134 --> 00:18:21,981
But after everyone had seen it, the teacher told me to take it back, for it was impossible to keep.

180
00:18:22,583 --> 00:18:24,405
Moles eat a lot of worms, it seems.

181
00:18:25,607 --> 00:18:31,876
Now, I don't know whether it was because it had bit me when I caught it, or whether I was angry at the teacher,

182
00:18:32,380 --> 00:18:35,765
or whether it was the result of past conditioning in cruelty.

183
00:18:36,766 --> 00:18:41,373
But, without really thinking about it, I took a large piece of wood and battered it to death.

184
00:18:43,275 --> 00:18:46,278
When that memory came back to me, I was filled with horror.

185
00:18:46,900 --> 00:18:48,021
I felt a certain panic.

186
00:18:49,222 --> 00:18:53,388
Even though I've meditated on it for years now, it still makes me feel uncomfortable.

187
00:18:54,490 --> 00:18:55,652
Such wanton cruelty.

188
00:18:56,874 --> 00:19:00,578
It's no good me arguing that perhaps the mole was getting his up-and-comers.

189
00:19:01,400 --> 00:19:01,881
I did it.

190
00:19:02,417 --> 00:19:03,818
I perform the foul deed.

191
00:19:05,240 --> 00:19:07,402
What the outer consequences are, I don't know.

192
00:19:07,501 --> 00:19:08,903
Perhaps I've already suffered them.

193
00:19:09,084 --> 00:19:09,584
I hope so.

194
00:19:10,664 --> 00:19:12,747
But I'm painfully aware of the inner consequences.

195
00:19:13,827 --> 00:19:21,535
But having observed all this in meditation and reflecting upon it, in time, the emotional power of the memory has decreased.

196
00:19:21,555 --> 00:19:22,715
This has been my karma.

197
00:19:26,479 --> 00:19:30,923
The first steps, then, in overcoming guilt feelings is to face up to them.

198
00:19:31,273 --> 00:19:33,477
and there's no better place than in the meditation.

199
00:19:34,838 --> 00:19:37,583
The second is to reflect on the act.

200
00:19:37,603 --> 00:19:43,330
There is a mistaken understanding that you can put things right, but the spilt milk is spilt, it is gone.

201
00:19:44,192 --> 00:19:49,499
That little mole cannot be resurrected, nor can its suffering be wiped out of history.

202
00:19:50,461 --> 00:19:52,703
All we can do is accept the consequences.

203
00:19:53,885 --> 00:19:57,931
Now in truth there's great relief in that, because now we can stop worrying.

204
00:19:58,692 --> 00:19:59,913
What will be, will be.

205
00:20:00,501 --> 00:20:05,846
though I can undermine unwholesome karma coming my way by doing wholesome things.

206
00:20:06,968 --> 00:20:10,191
One of the incidents in Mahatma Gandhi's life illustrates this well.

207
00:20:11,311 --> 00:20:16,817
A distraught Hindu came to him saying that he had killed a Muslim child during one of the riots.

208
00:20:17,298 --> 00:20:18,118
What bad karma!

209
00:20:19,440 --> 00:20:23,844
Gandhi told him to adopt a Muslim orphan and bring him up as a Muslim.

210
00:20:24,585 --> 00:20:29,209
This good deed would go a long way to counteract the earlier unskillful one.

211
00:20:30,556 --> 00:20:34,259
This is a very important point to grasp in the Buddha's teaching on karma.

212
00:20:34,861 --> 00:20:36,041
Nothing is preconditioned.

213
00:20:36,502 --> 00:20:42,210
We can assuage unwholesome consequences in the future by doing what is good now.

214
00:20:44,833 --> 00:20:50,459
There are further steps to purifying the mind of guilt, but this is dealt with in a later talk.

215
00:20:50,479 --> 00:20:53,383
Enough it is to say here that the first step is acceptance.

216
00:20:54,703 --> 00:21:00,411
If upon reflection we understand guilt to be unreal, an overreaction

217
00:21:00,661 --> 00:21:02,323
we will still have to suffer from it.

218
00:21:03,443 --> 00:21:06,886
We will still have to patiently allow it to rise up into our consciousness.

219
00:21:08,008 --> 00:21:15,615
However, in the process of letting go of such guilt, we can say that some part of the store of unresolved guilt is being expended.

220
00:21:17,337 --> 00:21:19,099
This needs a little further explanation.

221
00:21:20,121 --> 00:21:25,385
Although I've used terms like store of guilt, in Buddhist understanding this isn't quite right.

222
00:21:25,753 --> 00:21:32,041
What is more correct is to talk of a disposition, a tendency, which has been conditioned by past actions.

223
00:21:32,983 --> 00:21:38,931
If I tend to feel overguilty, then by allowing it to pass, that tendency will be weakened.

224
00:21:40,953 --> 00:21:43,758
Let us end with two salutary tales from the Dhammapada.

225
00:21:44,719 --> 00:21:46,480
First is the story of the careless monk.

226
00:21:47,321 --> 00:21:51,508
One of the rules of a monk's life is to put back whatever has been used.

227
00:21:52,500 --> 00:22:00,193
Now it was the habit of this monk that no matter what he used, table, stool or mat, he would leave it out in the open, exposed to the sun or the rain.

228
00:22:01,214 --> 00:22:07,726
When monks pointed this out to him, he just shrugged his shoulders, saying little damage was done, and anyway, he meant no harm.

229
00:22:09,067 --> 00:22:12,173
But he was warned that small faults are in the habit of growing large.

230
00:22:13,234 --> 00:22:15,979
He was a wise fellow after all, for he took their good counsel.

231
00:22:16,820 --> 00:22:18,323
When the Buddha heard this, he said,

232
00:22:18,943 --> 00:22:24,549
One should not think lightly of an unskillful deed, imagining, a little will not affect me.

233
00:22:25,611 --> 00:22:35,381
Just as a jug of water is filled by falling drops of rain, so also the fool is filled up with unwholesome conditioning by accumulating little by little.

234
00:22:39,203 --> 00:22:47,752
The second is the story of Billa Lepadika, a rich man who was ready to kill the organizer of a community offering of food to the Buddha and his monks.

235
00:22:48,829 --> 00:22:53,777
Bilal al-Padukah had been annoyed by this organizer for asking him and others to give.

236
00:22:54,557 --> 00:22:59,746
He noticed his small offering was kept apart and thought the organizer was doing this to show him up.

237
00:23:00,346 --> 00:23:01,749
That's why he was going to kill him.

238
00:23:02,809 --> 00:23:12,564
But in fact, the organizer put a little of what he had given in every bowl, thereby hoping to increase Bilal al-Padukah's merit.

239
00:23:12,584 --> 00:23:17,892
Bilal al-Padukah was repentant and apologized to the organizer for not supporting him properly.

240
00:23:18,361 --> 00:23:22,846
The Buddha overheard this and said, One should not think lightly of doing good.

241
00:23:23,445 --> 00:23:25,548
Imagining a little will not affect me.

242
00:23:26,390 --> 00:23:35,058
Just as a water jar is filled up with falling drops of rain, so also the wise one is filled up with merit, accumulated little by little.

243
00:23:37,060 --> 00:23:38,521
So there we have the Buddha's teaching.

244
00:23:38,903 --> 00:23:41,184
Be scrupulous about unskillful deeds.

245
00:23:41,746 --> 00:23:43,307
Do good no matter how small.

246
00:23:43,807 --> 00:23:44,689
It all counts.

247
00:23:47,622 --> 00:24:03,726
So when it comes to guilt and guilt feelings of low self-esteem, low self-respect, self-hatred, by doing what is wholesome, these are counteracted by feelings of high self-esteem, high self-respect, self-acceptance, self-care and self-understanding.

248
00:24:05,048 --> 00:24:13,359
By observing and sitting patiently with guilt feelings in meditation, we will purify the mind of anguish, remorse, anxiety and sorrow.

249
00:24:13,930 --> 00:24:25,625
And by doing what is wholesome and skillful in our daily lives, we will re-establish that sense of wholesomeness and innocence, which is the joy of being at peace with ourselves and at peace with the world.

250
00:24:29,990 --> 00:24:32,294
I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

251
00:24:33,295 --> 00:24:35,097
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

252
00:24:35,739 --> 00:24:38,402
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

